WEBVTT

00:08.080 --> 00:11.040
[ Horn honks, tires screech ]

00:11.040 --> 00:12.280
[ Crash, glass shatters ]

00:14.720 --> 00:16.520
HENRY:
The median nerve's been cut.

00:16.520 --> 00:19.400
Yes, I would say so.

00:19.400 --> 00:20.960
You are looking
for my replacement.

00:20.960 --> 00:22.200
I have suggestions.

00:22.200 --> 00:24.280
TheNeal Burton?

00:24.280 --> 00:26.640
-He's interested.
-Why would he want to come here?

00:26.640 --> 00:29.000
He said something about wanting
a change of scenery.

00:29.000 --> 00:32.320
You, Mr. Fox,
are going to be a father.

00:32.320 --> 00:34.600
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

00:34.600 --> 00:36.360
Miss Bligh, will you marry me?

00:36.360 --> 00:38.520
Don't tell me you are
stupid enough to marry Henry.

00:38.520 --> 00:39.680
All right, I won't.

00:39.680 --> 00:42.000
He's a ruddy shirt-lifter!

00:42.000 --> 00:44.120
Stop it.
Don't say that.

00:44.120 --> 00:45.560
You do not settle
for half a man!

00:45.560 --> 00:47.120
Well, Mama did,
so why shouldn't I?

00:48.760 --> 00:51.800
He loved your mother,
and she loved him.

00:51.800 --> 00:53.520
He killed her.

00:54.200 --> 00:55.640
With his baby.

00:55.640 --> 00:57.200
She's right, you know.

00:58.520 --> 01:00.320
Dawnie would be alive
if we hadn't met.

01:00.320 --> 01:01.760
Snap!

01:01.760 --> 01:03.040
MATT:
I can't be his father

01:03.040 --> 01:05.000
until I know whoever gave him up
doesn't regret it.

01:05.000 --> 01:09.000
He intends to follow through
on tracking Georgie's mother,

01:09.000 --> 01:11.360
whether or not you are involved.

01:11.360 --> 01:13.800
What was that charade about
earlier?

01:13.800 --> 01:15.880
"I'll respect your decision"?

01:15.880 --> 01:18.880
This is for you and Georgie.

01:18.880 --> 01:20.480
MATT:
We want you to find the records.

01:20.480 --> 01:23.120
I don't know if they've been
kept or where they'd be.

01:23.120 --> 01:24.960
Well, the police will help
if you can't.

01:24.960 --> 01:28.680
The, uh, papers have been found.

01:28.680 --> 01:30.480
He wants to see us.

01:30.480 --> 01:31.480
Tomorrow.

01:31.480 --> 01:33.800
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

01:35.000 --> 01:41.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:52.560 --> 01:56.000
[ Indistinct conversations,
telephone ringing ]

02:09.199 --> 02:11.440
[ Typewriters clicking
in distance ]

02:11.440 --> 02:14.440
So is that...

02:14.440 --> 02:16.080
That's her?

02:16.080 --> 02:18.840
It's, uh,
it's limited information.

02:18.840 --> 02:23.440
The young woman was unmarried
and unable to name the father.

02:23.440 --> 02:26.720
The baby would have been
a source of shame, sorrow.

02:26.720 --> 02:27.880
Of course.

02:27.880 --> 02:29.560
If the child hadn't gone to you,

02:29.560 --> 02:32.280
it would have gone to another
couple who wanted a child.

02:32.280 --> 02:33.960
The question is,
was it her decision,

02:33.960 --> 02:35.880
or was she under pressure?

02:35.880 --> 02:38.640
Some girls have their
own mothers raise the child.

02:39.200 --> 02:41.440
Well, this has jogged my memory
somewhat.

02:41.440 --> 02:43.520
There was discussion at the time
about the child

02:43.520 --> 02:46.080
having been conceived
in difficult circumstances.

02:46.080 --> 02:49.560
S-So she would have wanted him
placed in a family.

02:49.560 --> 02:51.560
Almost certainly, yes.

02:51.560 --> 02:54.440
She may not even want to talk
to us at all.

02:54.440 --> 02:57.240
As I've said before, I can't
really see the value for you

02:57.240 --> 02:59.560
or for her
in bringing it all up again.

02:59.560 --> 03:03.160
We need you to contact her
so we can know for ourselves.

03:03.800 --> 03:06.480
Yes. Well, the difficulty is, of
course, that, um, people move.

03:06.480 --> 03:09.200
Women marry.
Tracking her may not be easy.

03:09.200 --> 03:11.440
Our son -- Olivia's son --

03:11.440 --> 03:13.520
has a birth certificate
with your signature,

03:13.520 --> 03:16.440
with Olivia and James Bligh
named as mother and father.

03:16.440 --> 03:19.200
There was no legal adoption.

03:21.800 --> 03:23.440
Very well.

03:26.720 --> 03:28.240
Do you want me to try?

03:32.320 --> 03:33.600
Yes.

03:35.360 --> 03:36.680
Yes, we do.

03:40.960 --> 03:43.960
[ Birds chirping ]

03:45.280 --> 03:48.680
Mummy!
Cook said you forgot.

03:48.680 --> 03:50.680
Oh!
I did.

03:50.680 --> 03:52.840
Well, thank you
for looking after me.

03:52.840 --> 03:54.640
See you later, alligator.

03:54.640 --> 03:56.040
After work, Mr. Bourke.

03:56.040 --> 03:57.440
[ Laughs ]

03:57.440 --> 03:59.560
-Bye!
-Bye-bye!

03:59.560 --> 04:02.080
[ Birds chirping ]

04:04.600 --> 04:05.720
Papa?

04:08.160 --> 04:09.680
May I?

04:20.640 --> 04:23.520
I'm so ashamed about what I said
last night.

04:23.520 --> 04:25.200
I'm sorry.

04:25.200 --> 04:28.400
It's not what I think.
It just came out.

04:29.640 --> 04:32.120
Well, you were standing up
for yourself, I suppose.

04:32.120 --> 04:36.160
No, I was being cruel,
and I regret it.

04:38.760 --> 04:40.320
And I regret what I said
about Henry.

04:42.880 --> 04:44.200
We're both hot-headed.

04:46.600 --> 04:49.680
Could we rewind and pretend
none of it was said?

04:51.680 --> 04:53.560
Zz-z-z-z-t!

04:53.560 --> 04:55.520
[ Laughs ]

04:55.520 --> 04:56.760
Rewound.

05:01.680 --> 05:03.680
I've been thinking
that with Mama away,

05:03.680 --> 05:07.320
I might offer to step in for her
at the women's clinic.

05:07.320 --> 05:08.360
What do you think?

05:08.360 --> 05:10.200
Promise to stay out
of your hair.

05:12.040 --> 05:13.840
Is that a genuine question?

05:13.840 --> 05:16.320
Well, it isyour hospital,
and Henry's.

05:16.320 --> 05:19.840
I think you don't even go
into Inverness,

05:19.840 --> 05:22.040
not in your condition.

05:22.040 --> 05:25.120
You stay away from Doris.
You stay away from the town.

05:26.040 --> 05:28.080
Don't they need to get used
to the idea?

05:28.080 --> 05:30.880
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

05:30.880 --> 05:32.480
I'm interviewing someone.
Excuse me.

05:32.480 --> 05:33.840
Papa.

05:33.840 --> 05:36.000
At the very least --
the verylest --

05:36.000 --> 05:37.640
have some respect
for this family.

05:38.400 --> 05:40.240
To the world, you are a Bligh.

05:40.240 --> 05:42.240
Act like one.

05:45.440 --> 05:48.760
You do know that we're trying
to protect you.

05:48.760 --> 05:50.360
Times will change.

05:50.360 --> 05:53.000
A rocket will take a man
into outer space someday.

05:53.680 --> 05:55.280
Until then...

05:55.280 --> 05:58.840
Father, the baby
that I'm carrying is a miracle,

05:58.840 --> 06:00.880
and that's partly why
I want to hold my head up high

06:00.880 --> 06:04.280
and share my...my pride.

06:04.280 --> 06:06.280
I could bring hope to women
who come into the clinic

06:06.280 --> 06:08.360
worried that they'll
never conceive.

06:08.360 --> 06:10.760
No woman around here
will think that.

06:10.760 --> 06:12.640
So it's off to the home
for fallen girls?

06:12.640 --> 06:16.240
We can control the gossip here.
Much less so out there.

06:16.240 --> 06:19.720
Don't play into the hands
of the likes of Stan O'Rourke.

06:19.720 --> 06:23.160
Well, they're going to have to
get used to it sooner or later.

06:23.160 --> 06:25.120
I'm not ashamed.

06:25.120 --> 06:27.160
[ Clock ticking ]

06:29.440 --> 06:31.240
Marry Henry.

06:31.240 --> 06:36.160
Even if you marry and divorce,
give your child a chance.

06:40.480 --> 06:42.520
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

06:54.920 --> 06:57.160
[ Vehicle approaching ]

07:03.400 --> 07:06.040
[ Brake clicks,
engine shuts off ]

07:10.040 --> 07:12.640
Good morning, Sister Bligh.

07:12.640 --> 07:15.240
Might I have a word to you
about young Emma?

07:15.240 --> 07:16.600
[ Exhales sharply ]

07:16.600 --> 07:18.520
It's just I've been up with her
most of the night.

07:18.520 --> 07:21.240
She's just so terribly,
terribly distressed.

07:21.240 --> 07:23.280
Well, perhaps Dr. Duncan
can see her,

07:23.280 --> 07:25.080
prescribe her something
to help her sleep.

07:25.080 --> 07:27.240
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

07:27.240 --> 07:29.600
[ Engine revs ]

07:29.600 --> 07:32.560
Oi! You!
I'm talking to you.

07:32.560 --> 07:34.880
-Mr. Bailey, what do you want?
-Watch yourself, Jacko!

07:34.880 --> 07:36.520
The witches have arrived!

07:36.520 --> 07:39.200
Stan's missus and kids
not enough for youse, eh?

07:39.200 --> 07:42.120
Shut that clinic down
or it'll get shut down for you,

07:42.120 --> 07:43.680
you home-wrecking tarts.

07:44.560 --> 07:46.680
Let's go.
[ Spits ]

07:46.680 --> 07:49.120
[ Engine revs ]

07:52.840 --> 07:54.880
Oh!

08:18.360 --> 08:20.520
-[ Knock on door ]
-Yes.

08:22.120 --> 08:24.880
Neil Burton, Jack Duncan.

08:24.880 --> 08:26.080
Mr. Burton, welcome.

08:26.080 --> 08:27.960
Neil, please.

08:27.960 --> 08:30.640
Ah.
Thanks so much for coming.

08:30.640 --> 08:31.720
Good trip up?

08:31.720 --> 08:33.120
Shorter than one thinks.

08:33.120 --> 08:34.280
Please.

08:34.280 --> 08:36.400
I'll stand for a while
if you don't mind.

08:37.000 --> 08:39.600
Uh, some tea?

08:39.600 --> 08:41.120
I'll take a look around first,
I think.

08:41.120 --> 08:42.679
If you'd prefer.

08:42.679 --> 08:44.720
Well, at least we've got
some space here to expand.

08:44.720 --> 08:46.320
That's a plus.

08:46.320 --> 08:48.240
They're running out of land
at the Prince of Wales.

08:48.240 --> 08:50.760
Buildings crammed up
like something in Calcutta.

08:50.760 --> 08:52.400
We have hoped for some time

08:52.400 --> 08:54.800
that this hospital could become
a regional hub.

08:54.800 --> 08:57.840
I assume that was your argument
for your new surgical wing.

08:57.840 --> 09:00.920
Oh. All going well.
That's stage one.

09:00.920 --> 09:02.480
Actually, the minister's
talking up this area

09:02.480 --> 09:03.960
as the next
state health district.

09:03.960 --> 09:05.960
That's the latest jargon.

09:05.960 --> 09:08.360
I had a round of golf with him
after we spoke.

09:08.360 --> 09:10.400
Your board's been in his ear,
I believe.

09:10.400 --> 09:12.520
[ Telephone ringing
in distance ]

09:12.520 --> 09:15.760
It's all about specialization
these days.

09:15.760 --> 09:17.440
Any thoughts on adding to these?

09:18.760 --> 09:21.040
Not at the moment, no.

09:21.680 --> 09:23.560
Oh. Well, no problem.
Just wondering.

09:23.560 --> 09:26.760
We're kept on our toes here,
really.

09:26.760 --> 09:30.560
Probably a more interesting mix
of cases than, uh...

09:31.640 --> 09:33.880
Well, plenty of variety.

09:33.880 --> 09:35.720
Let's put it that way.

09:35.720 --> 09:39.560
Still, you might want to add
to that degree down the track.

09:39.560 --> 09:42.440
With the advances in medical
technology over the next years,

09:42.440 --> 09:45.080
we're in for a very
interesting ride, I think.

09:46.720 --> 09:48.480
Shall we give Neil
the guided tour?

09:48.480 --> 09:50.320
Unfortunately I have a patient.

09:50.320 --> 09:52.760
-I couldn't cancel.
-Oh. Of course. Of course.

09:52.760 --> 09:53.920
I'll catch you up.

09:53.920 --> 09:55.200
Excellent.

09:56.160 --> 09:58.680
So what are you thinking,
old chap?

09:58.680 --> 10:00.560
Median's done like a dinner.
And the flexor tendon.

10:00.560 --> 10:02.280
Oh, that's bloody bad luck.

10:02.280 --> 10:04.120
But I don't need to tell you
that.

10:04.120 --> 10:07.200
HENRY: I'm lined up to see
Benjamin Frank for surgery.

10:07.200 --> 10:11.160
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

10:39.640 --> 10:41.480
[ Music continues ]

10:51.120 --> 10:54.840
You were a wonderful student,
and you're a marvelous surgeon.

10:54.840 --> 10:58.080
You're not destined
to lick stamps behind a desk.

10:58.080 --> 11:00.120
Sounds like it.

11:00.120 --> 11:03.200
To my way of thinking,
you stay on here as my 2IC,

11:03.200 --> 11:04.960
take on general medicine.

11:04.960 --> 11:07.560
We build this place together.

11:07.560 --> 11:10.320
Depending on your outcome, you
could do the simpler surgery.

11:10.320 --> 11:11.840
Oh.
I don't think so.

11:11.840 --> 11:14.360
Well, then you assist me
pre- and post-op.

11:14.360 --> 11:15.680
Make sense?

11:17.000 --> 11:18.920
This Dr. Duncan,
he's -- he's been here yonks.

11:18.920 --> 11:21.200
He's basically a GP.

11:21.200 --> 11:23.880
He's very well liked.
Very.

11:23.880 --> 11:25.280
He's a pleasant enough chap,

11:25.280 --> 11:27.800
but resting on what might
loosely be called his laurels.

11:29.920 --> 11:33.120
He's the backbone of this place.
The staff are devoted to him.

11:33.120 --> 11:35.080
He's stuck.

11:35.080 --> 11:36.720
The next decade's upon us.

11:36.720 --> 11:38.560
There's no place for fossils
in it.

11:40.280 --> 11:41.920
Where to now?

11:44.080 --> 11:46.520
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

11:57.280 --> 11:59.400
Are you sure, Mrs. Costas?

11:59.400 --> 12:00.320
[ Door opens ]

12:02.040 --> 12:05.000
Well, if you change your mind
or if it would help,

12:05.000 --> 12:06.440
I could talk to Mr. Costas.

12:06.440 --> 12:08.240
I...

12:08.240 --> 12:10.360
Uh, no.
I understand.

12:11.120 --> 12:13.040
Thank you.

12:13.040 --> 12:14.800
-Good morning.
-Bad time?

12:14.800 --> 12:15.920
No.
Just a surprise.

12:15.920 --> 12:17.320
How can I help?

12:17.320 --> 12:20.000
Well, I was thinking
that I could help you --

12:20.000 --> 12:21.840
here, fill in for Mama.

12:21.840 --> 12:24.560
Give you a bit of time
to go into town.

12:24.560 --> 12:27.080
You were saying you'd like to
take David to the synagogue.

12:27.080 --> 12:29.760
Or maybe you and Father
could see a show.

12:29.760 --> 12:31.480
I do shorthand,

12:31.480 --> 12:33.560
and I've been known
to take instructions.

12:33.560 --> 12:35.680
And I can operate a Gestetner.

12:35.680 --> 12:38.160
Well, I can't do that,
but I could learn.

12:38.160 --> 12:40.200
Well, I thought you would like
an appointment.

12:40.840 --> 12:41.840
Not yet.

12:41.840 --> 12:43.240
And just so you know --

12:43.240 --> 12:45.560
Papa, he doesn't think this is
a good idea.

12:45.560 --> 12:47.800
-But he'll come 'round.
-And where are we with Henry?

12:48.480 --> 12:50.200
Muddling through.

12:50.200 --> 12:52.800
[ Engine starts, revs
in distance ]

12:53.520 --> 12:56.320
How do I put this?
Um...

12:56.720 --> 12:59.600
"As broad-minded as I am..."

12:59.600 --> 13:01.080
Go ahead.

13:03.320 --> 13:05.600
One man threatened
to burn this place down

13:05.600 --> 13:07.200
because his wife left him.

13:07.200 --> 13:10.200
I've just had abuse
from some of his mates

13:10.200 --> 13:13.000
and two cancellations just now.

13:13.600 --> 13:16.000
We think we're providing
a much-needed service.

13:16.000 --> 13:19.920
But to others, mainly men,
we're destroying families,

13:19.920 --> 13:22.360
tearing down the moral fabric.

13:22.360 --> 13:25.680
Not only tearing it down,
but draping ourselves in it

13:25.680 --> 13:28.480
and dancing naked
under the full moon.

13:28.480 --> 13:31.200
And a deviant woman
would add to the brew.

13:31.200 --> 13:33.480
[ Gasps ]
Miss Anna!

13:33.480 --> 13:36.760
I heard you were back
from Hawaii!

13:36.760 --> 13:38.240
Thank you.

13:38.240 --> 13:40.560
Doris was also the brunt
of the abuse this morning.

13:40.560 --> 13:42.320
DORIS:
Oh, indeed, indeed.

13:42.320 --> 13:45.720
I keep seeing the whole thing
in slow motion.

13:45.720 --> 13:47.600
-Oh, Miss Anna!
-[ Laughs ]

13:47.600 --> 13:49.920
How lovely to have you back!

13:49.920 --> 13:51.680
Thank you, Mrs. Collins.

13:51.680 --> 13:53.240
You're...

13:53.240 --> 13:54.360
Yes.

13:54.360 --> 13:56.160
And you've...

13:56.840 --> 14:01.240
Sometimes the ladies' fingers --
They -- They can't wear the...

14:01.240 --> 14:03.640
No, I'm not married,
Mrs. Collins.

14:03.640 --> 14:05.560
And I'm having a baby.

14:05.560 --> 14:08.360
The two things,
they don't always go together.

14:08.360 --> 14:10.760
Oh.
I see.

14:10.760 --> 14:13.000
Oh.
Well, it's...

14:13.000 --> 14:14.640
That's interesting.
Yeah.

14:15.440 --> 14:17.880
All right.
Well, excuse me, miss.

14:25.680 --> 14:28.280
Nothing will ever change
until people are challenged.

14:28.280 --> 14:31.000
Same goes for those bullies
out there.

14:31.000 --> 14:33.360
It's not like you
to just cave in.

14:33.360 --> 14:36.960
Or you could keep a low profile
until controversy dies down.

14:36.960 --> 14:39.440
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

14:40.080 --> 14:41.680
Anna, I...

14:52.240 --> 14:54.280
Good timing.

14:54.280 --> 14:55.800
Where's Dr. Duncan, please?

14:55.800 --> 14:57.960
He was called
to the delivery ward, sir.

14:57.960 --> 14:59.040
Oh.

14:59.040 --> 15:01.480
Well, while we're waiting --

15:01.480 --> 15:02.840
Ah.

15:02.840 --> 15:06.720
Mr. Fox, I just slipped a note
under your door.

15:06.720 --> 15:08.560
Mr. Neil Burton,
it's my pleasure to introduce

15:08.560 --> 15:10.240
Miss Anna Bligh.

15:10.240 --> 15:11.920
Mr. Burton is visiting us
from Sydney.

15:11.920 --> 15:13.320
Pleased to meet you.

15:13.320 --> 15:15.480
My wife has read all your books.

15:15.480 --> 15:17.160
Oh.
How wonderful to hear.

15:17.160 --> 15:18.480
But I must run.

15:18.480 --> 15:19.640
If you'll excuse me.

15:19.640 --> 15:21.560
It was lovely to meet you,
Mr. Burton.

15:21.560 --> 15:23.160
No rush.

15:25.040 --> 15:26.440
Miss Bligh?

15:26.440 --> 15:28.640
She's leaving a bit late
to head to the altar.

15:28.640 --> 15:31.960
Wife won't be too impressed.
I'll say that much.

15:31.960 --> 15:33.960
They're certainly a worry,
daughters.

15:33.960 --> 15:36.840
I still have two on my hands.

15:36.840 --> 15:38.200
Actually, I've proposed to her.

15:39.480 --> 15:41.200
To Miss Bligh.

15:41.200 --> 15:42.880
You'd take on
another chap's child?

15:43.600 --> 15:45.680
No.
I'm the father.

15:46.560 --> 15:48.640
Well, you two
had better hurry up, then.

15:48.640 --> 15:50.360
Unless you want
your fiancée's books

15:50.360 --> 15:53.400
tossed into
the proverbial bonfire.

15:53.400 --> 15:56.000
Look, I think it best
you thank Dr. Duncan for me.

15:56.000 --> 15:57.880
I'll be in touch.

16:00.160 --> 16:01.880
Good news on the marriage.

16:01.880 --> 16:03.640
Won't do your reputation
any harm.

16:05.280 --> 16:07.520
In fact,
it'll do it the world of good.

16:07.520 --> 16:09.640
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

16:13.240 --> 16:16.160
MATT:
Yeah. Yes.

16:17.600 --> 16:18.840
Right.

16:20.320 --> 16:22.680
Yes, Doctor.
We realize that.

16:22.680 --> 16:24.440
It's number 29, correct?

16:25.080 --> 16:26.720
Good day to you.

16:32.120 --> 16:34.600
She wants to meet with us.

16:34.600 --> 16:36.120
This afternoon.

16:37.400 --> 16:39.400
She only lives in Strathfield.

16:39.400 --> 16:42.720
Her name is Avril Newman.

16:43.280 --> 16:44.160
Miss.

16:44.800 --> 16:46.240
Did she...

16:47.680 --> 16:49.160
Did she say why?

16:53.800 --> 16:55.880
We're not taking Georgie.

16:55.880 --> 16:58.160
She can't make us do that.

16:58.160 --> 17:00.680
How about I go
in the first instance,

17:00.680 --> 17:02.640
understand her expectations?

17:05.720 --> 17:07.200
I'm so afraid.

17:07.200 --> 17:09.079
And that's why I'll go first,
yeah?

17:09.079 --> 17:11.920
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

17:11.920 --> 17:14.760
Be discreet, won't you?

17:14.760 --> 17:18.400
You can say that James and I
separated amicably.

17:18.400 --> 17:20.839
She doesn't need to know
any more than that.

17:28.359 --> 17:30.880
[ Train passing in distance ]

17:30.880 --> 17:32.920
[ Music continues ]

17:40.600 --> 17:42.880
[ Hinges squeak ]

17:53.720 --> 17:56.160
"And is this the extent of
your qualifications, old chap?

17:56.160 --> 17:57.480
Is this the best you can do?"

17:57.480 --> 17:59.000
He didn't say that.

17:59.000 --> 18:03.080
It's like one of those Pommy
captains we had in the war.

18:03.080 --> 18:04.960
If I couldn't work
with the old Henry,

18:04.960 --> 18:06.560
I sure as heck can't work
with this bloke.

18:06.560 --> 18:07.760
He is very good, though.

18:07.760 --> 18:09.480
There are plenty
of other medicos out there.

18:09.480 --> 18:10.640
Life's too short.

18:10.640 --> 18:12.240
Henry certainly wouldn't be able
to cop him.

18:12.240 --> 18:13.520
That's a shame.

18:13.520 --> 18:15.840
When I asked him a question,
he answered Henry.

18:15.840 --> 18:17.280
-One of those.
-One of those.

18:17.280 --> 18:18.960
Never actually spoken
to a nurse.

18:18.960 --> 18:21.640
That's it.
You're all a blur of white.

18:21.640 --> 18:22.720
-"Next."
-"Next."

18:22.720 --> 18:23.640
[ Both laugh ]

18:25.960 --> 18:27.160
[ Birds chirping ]

18:27.160 --> 18:28.880
Henry!

18:28.880 --> 18:30.960
-Miss Bligh.
-That was quick.

18:30.960 --> 18:33.160
I didn't mean for you
to take time out of your work.

18:33.160 --> 18:34.840
I'm a supernumerary
at the moment.

18:34.840 --> 18:36.080
Anyway, that may change.

18:38.760 --> 18:42.560
I couldn't quite glean
your response from this.

18:42.560 --> 18:45.520
I assumed you were being
discreet.

18:45.520 --> 18:47.040
Henry.

18:47.040 --> 18:49.760
[ Sighs ]
Are you serious?

18:49.760 --> 18:52.480
For God's sakes Anna,
we'd be perfect.

18:52.480 --> 18:55.000
-You're not thinking clearly.
-I am, I'm afraid.

18:57.760 --> 18:59.880
"Mummy, why do all the other
children call me a bastard?"

18:59.880 --> 19:01.560
Stop.

19:01.560 --> 19:03.520
"Because even though your father
wanted to marry me, love me,

19:03.520 --> 19:07.240
support me, have a --
a fun-filled life together,

19:07.240 --> 19:08.960
I refused him
to make some social point,

19:08.960 --> 19:10.320
which failed miserably,

19:10.320 --> 19:11.880
and now you'll suffer
for the rest of your life."

19:11.880 --> 19:14.480
Attitudes to single mothers
will change.

19:15.600 --> 19:18.000
And my type will become
prime minister one day.

19:19.040 --> 19:21.320
[ Sighs ]

19:21.320 --> 19:23.160
[ Birds chirping ]

19:24.760 --> 19:28.000
Our little haven.
That's what we said.

19:28.000 --> 19:30.560
We'd be marrying
because I fell pregnant.

19:30.560 --> 19:32.880
It's as good a reason as any.

19:33.440 --> 19:35.680
W-We could carve our own way.

19:37.120 --> 19:38.160
I can't.

19:41.720 --> 19:44.600
Well, just a word
from the front line.

19:44.600 --> 19:46.560
Fighting shame ain't
what it's cracked up to be.

19:48.360 --> 19:51.080
Henry, you'll always
be involved.

19:52.560 --> 19:54.160
Wrapped up
in your grand statement

19:54.160 --> 19:56.320
against church and state,

19:56.320 --> 19:58.840
against your family
and God knows what else.

19:59.480 --> 20:01.800
I'm not sure I want to be part
of that.

20:02.760 --> 20:03.880
Well, I want you to.

20:20.320 --> 20:22.680
[ Engine shuts off ]

20:22.680 --> 20:25.120
[ Brake clicks, keys jingle ]

20:29.120 --> 20:30.920
OLIVIA:
[ Chuckles ]

20:30.920 --> 20:33.080
-MATT: Hello!
-Out here!

20:36.440 --> 20:37.920
Elizabeth.

20:39.240 --> 20:42.000
I asked Elizabeth over
to join me.

20:43.960 --> 20:45.000
What happened?

20:47.040 --> 20:48.960
Georgie's gone up to the house.

20:51.960 --> 20:53.400
Well, she lives with her mother.

20:54.360 --> 20:55.960
She's now 22.

20:56.600 --> 20:58.040
She asked a lot of questions.

20:58.040 --> 21:00.160
Such as?

21:00.720 --> 21:06.480
His name, is he happy,
what he likes to do,

21:06.480 --> 21:08.840
what sort of a life he has.

21:09.440 --> 21:11.040
And?

21:13.240 --> 21:14.480
And she wants to meet him.

21:15.280 --> 21:16.120
And you.

21:18.800 --> 21:20.200
No.

21:21.240 --> 21:23.320
-No.
-It's her right, Livvy.

21:24.320 --> 21:26.320
Did she give him up willingly?

21:26.320 --> 21:27.840
That is all you needed
to find out.

21:27.840 --> 21:29.360
It wasn't something
she could answer.

21:29.360 --> 21:31.360
She either did or she didn't.

21:31.360 --> 21:33.560
Why couldn't she answer that?

21:33.560 --> 21:36.320
I promised her we'd come back
tomorrow.

21:36.320 --> 21:37.840
We have to hear her out.

21:37.840 --> 21:40.160
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

21:43.000 --> 21:45.400
Would you both...excuse me?

21:48.880 --> 21:51.240
I think it's best tomorrow.

21:55.000 --> 21:58.440
Why not let her do this
at her own pace?

22:00.760 --> 22:03.920
'Cause sometimes the Band-Aid
has to be ripped off.

22:04.520 --> 22:09.960
You express empathy for Olivia,
but can you actually feel it?

22:09.960 --> 22:12.000
Can you feel empathy for a woman

22:12.000 --> 22:14.040
who's lost her child
and wants to embrace him?

22:14.040 --> 22:16.040
I can.

22:16.040 --> 22:19.080
What is Georgie going to make
of this?

22:19.080 --> 22:22.000
A stranger hugging him,
weeping over him.

22:22.000 --> 22:23.720
It is cruel.

22:23.720 --> 22:26.080
If she makes a case
for having him back,

22:26.080 --> 22:27.720
then she won't be a stranger
for long.

22:31.480 --> 22:34.480
This is my great-grandson
we are talking about.

22:34.480 --> 22:36.240
He's not a parcel.

22:36.240 --> 22:38.600
He's not a bill of goods.

22:41.480 --> 22:42.880
From this family's
point of view,

22:42.880 --> 22:46.480
you are behaving most harshly,

22:46.480 --> 22:48.680
and you should put a stop
to this.

22:48.680 --> 22:50.560
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

22:57.080 --> 22:59.480
That's the problem right there.

22:59.480 --> 23:01.600
You people are incapable
of seeing anything

23:01.600 --> 23:03.040
other than your own point
of view.

23:04.600 --> 23:06.440
Our way or the highway.

23:09.000 --> 23:10.760
You really don't like us,
do you?

23:11.440 --> 23:13.840
Individually, yes.

23:13.840 --> 23:18.120
Collectively...
I reserve my judgment.

23:20.720 --> 23:22.560
[ Music continues ]

23:23.960 --> 23:25.160
Georgie darling?

23:26.400 --> 23:27.880
All right.

23:28.840 --> 23:30.960
Oh.
Quick sticks!

23:30.960 --> 23:34.040
We are going on an adventure.

23:35.480 --> 23:37.720
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

24:04.280 --> 24:06.840
Just checking the fine print.

24:06.840 --> 24:08.240
There isn't any, Delia.

24:08.240 --> 24:11.560
Oh, I trust you, James,
but thousands wouldn't.

24:11.560 --> 24:14.320
We are in business.

24:17.560 --> 24:21.120
Can't you wait until
this Georgie matter is settled?

24:21.120 --> 24:23.640
That's why I brought
my flight forward.

24:23.640 --> 24:25.760
If I thought it would help
Georgie in any way, I'd stay,

24:25.760 --> 24:29.560
but...my being here is
just adding to the complication.

24:30.560 --> 24:32.440
I have to leave it to Livvy
and Matt.

24:36.480 --> 24:39.600
Oh, Carolyn's idea
for the Australian letterhead.

24:39.600 --> 24:43.240
Cap-Ferrat, Sydney, Melbourne.

24:43.240 --> 24:45.840
Melbourne's a white lie --
for now.

24:45.840 --> 24:47.440
JAMES:
I like it.

24:48.280 --> 24:50.320
Perhaps my name
is slightly larger font.

24:50.320 --> 24:52.240
We won't let you down.

24:52.240 --> 24:54.480
Thought never crossed my mind.
Now --

24:54.480 --> 24:56.760
Excuse me, Mr. Bligh.
Um, Mrs. Bligh is here.

24:56.760 --> 24:58.440
She'd like to see you.

24:58.440 --> 25:01.800
She said to tell you that
she has Master Bligh with her.

25:01.800 --> 25:02.840
Where are they?

25:02.840 --> 25:05.360
On the veranda
at the moment, sir.

25:05.360 --> 25:07.240
Would you please do
two ice cream cones?

25:07.240 --> 25:09.320
-Quick as you can.
-Yes, Mrs. Duncan.

25:09.320 --> 25:11.600
I'll keep Georgie occupied.
Send Olivia in?

25:11.600 --> 25:13.320
Sitting room.

25:15.400 --> 25:16.840
I'll be back.

25:20.560 --> 25:22.800
[ Birds chirping ]

25:25.880 --> 25:27.520
We're finding lizards.

25:27.520 --> 25:30.840
Ah! Do lizards like ice cream
or is it little boys?

25:30.840 --> 25:32.920
Little boys!

25:32.920 --> 25:35.080
I might just pop inside.

25:35.080 --> 25:38.080
Good idea.
Take your time.

25:39.720 --> 25:45.440
Did you know there is
an old bird nest in that tree?

25:45.440 --> 25:48.160
We can do this.
Just...start a whole new life.

25:48.160 --> 25:49.280
Matt can't stop us.

25:49.280 --> 25:50.960
JAMES:
You'd only be making it worse.

25:51.640 --> 25:54.320
If you were to leave the country
now, with Georgie, this --

25:54.320 --> 25:55.960
Think about it.
This woman, this --

25:55.960 --> 25:57.320
It doesn't matter her name.

25:57.320 --> 25:58.680
I only told you that
because we know it now,

25:58.680 --> 26:00.280
not because it matters
who she is.

26:00.280 --> 26:02.000
If she chose to lay claim
to Georgie...

26:02.000 --> 26:03.280
Don't even think it.

26:03.280 --> 26:04.480
...you'd be compounding
the problem.

26:04.480 --> 26:07.160
The law could call it kidnapping
for all we know.

26:10.640 --> 26:11.960
You don't want him anymore,
do you?

26:11.960 --> 26:13.240
Livvy.

26:13.240 --> 26:16.560
If you did,
you'd be out there now.

26:16.560 --> 26:19.360
You couldn't stand
not being with him.

26:19.360 --> 26:22.400
Seeing me again for such a short
time would only confuse him.

26:22.400 --> 26:24.680
I'd be leaving him
all over again.

26:24.680 --> 26:26.160
We decided that.

26:26.840 --> 26:30.160
But you'll accept his going off
to a perfect stranger.

26:30.160 --> 26:32.320
But it might not happen.
Probably won'thappen.

26:32.320 --> 26:33.600
One step at a time.

26:36.320 --> 26:38.920
She's the kidnapper,
not me, James.

26:38.920 --> 26:41.720
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

26:52.920 --> 26:54.800
Look.

27:01.520 --> 27:03.840
JAMES: He still likes
his Matchbox cars.

27:04.640 --> 27:08.480
There are times when I rue
the day you started him off.

27:13.920 --> 27:16.440
You come whenever you want to.

27:17.320 --> 27:19.760
But you must clear things
with this woman first.

27:23.760 --> 27:26.560
[ Music continues ]

27:26.560 --> 27:29.960
The only reason
I agreed to find her was...

27:29.960 --> 27:32.280
to save my relationship.

27:33.240 --> 27:36.920
Selfish, really,
when you think about it.

27:37.720 --> 27:39.000
You love Matt.

27:40.040 --> 27:41.520
Yes.

27:42.240 --> 27:44.920
And do you think you'll still
love him when this is over,

27:44.920 --> 27:46.920
whichever way it goes?

27:50.040 --> 27:53.480
You are the strongest woman
I know.

27:56.640 --> 27:58.120
Remember that.

28:00.920 --> 28:03.240
Once you've seen her,
telegram me with any news.

28:03.240 --> 28:05.400
I'll phone immediately.

28:05.400 --> 28:06.840
I always will.

28:09.600 --> 28:12.120
OLIVIA:
[ Sobs ]

28:16.960 --> 28:20.360
My goodness!
Olivia!

28:20.360 --> 28:22.440
Oh, I thought you were
one of the maids!

28:22.440 --> 28:24.760
They're always crying
over something.

28:24.760 --> 28:26.760
I'm -- I'm so sorry.

28:26.760 --> 28:28.920
I-I just needed to...

28:28.920 --> 28:31.040
Of course.
Of course.

28:31.040 --> 28:32.840
What's happened?

28:32.840 --> 28:34.240
I've...

28:35.440 --> 28:38.480
Oh, I've made such a mess
of things!

28:38.480 --> 28:40.520
[ Sobs ]

28:41.480 --> 28:42.800
Oh.

28:43.840 --> 28:46.040
If you wish to share...

28:47.840 --> 28:51.720
Oh, please. Don't --
Don't let my garb deter.

28:51.720 --> 28:53.480
Yoga.
It's quite the thing.

28:53.480 --> 28:55.720
[ Laughs ]

28:55.720 --> 29:01.040
You know, my Andrew holds you
in such high esteem.

29:01.040 --> 29:03.520
He's always asking after you.

29:04.680 --> 29:06.840
-Is he?
-Mm.

29:08.040 --> 29:10.280
How ironic.

29:10.280 --> 29:13.000
I've been thinking about Andrew,
actually.

29:13.000 --> 29:15.480
Have you?

29:16.040 --> 29:17.200
All this.

29:18.800 --> 29:21.160
This is all Andrew's work...

29:23.000 --> 29:25.200
...and if things end badly...

29:26.880 --> 29:28.440
...Andrew's fault.

29:32.400 --> 29:35.080
I don't know what you mean,
dear.

29:35.680 --> 29:37.360
My Andrew?

29:38.680 --> 29:40.560
Andrew Swanson?

29:41.480 --> 29:44.000
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

29:44.000 --> 29:46.320
[ Birds chirping ]

29:47.800 --> 29:49.640
I don't know where they are.

29:49.640 --> 29:50.840
[ Keys jingling ]

29:50.840 --> 29:52.880
They could be anywhere.

29:53.520 --> 29:55.200
Let's just pray she hasn't done
something stupid

29:55.200 --> 29:56.360
and taken Georgie with her.

29:56.360 --> 29:57.800
Olivia wouldn't.

29:57.800 --> 30:00.840
It's exactly
what desperate women do.

30:00.840 --> 30:03.360
I don't know if anyone else
realizes this in your family,

30:03.360 --> 30:06.320
but Olivia is, deep down,
a very fragile girl.

30:08.160 --> 30:09.200
What, you don't agree?

30:11.760 --> 30:13.720
I'm sure she'll be back soon.

30:13.720 --> 30:15.920
[ Clock ticking ]

30:15.920 --> 30:18.200
She called you while I was out.
You know where they are.

30:18.200 --> 30:19.320
[ Door closes ]

30:19.320 --> 30:21.280
Ah.
[ Chuckles ]

30:22.360 --> 30:25.320
-Guess what, Grandma!
-Oh, I give up.

30:25.320 --> 30:28.680
Aunt Caro gave me two ice creams
and said don't tell.

30:28.680 --> 30:30.360
You funny sausage!

30:30.360 --> 30:32.920
-Scallywag.
-[ Chuckles ] Right. Come on.

30:32.920 --> 30:34.960
Tell Grammy what else
you've been up to.

30:34.960 --> 30:37.040
-Birds' nests.
-Oh!

30:37.040 --> 30:38.960
-Lizards.
-Birds' nests.

30:38.960 --> 30:40.160
GEORGIE:
Two.

30:42.520 --> 30:45.440
I called the Swansons'.
Maid said you weren't there.

30:45.440 --> 30:48.000
I've been worried sick, driving
around trying to find you.

30:48.000 --> 30:50.000
[ Clock ticking ]

30:50.000 --> 30:53.280
We'll go to see her tomorrow.

30:54.280 --> 30:57.040
You're right.
It's pointless to delay.

30:57.040 --> 30:58.920
I'll telephone her
and make a time.

30:58.920 --> 31:02.120
I've decided to take Elizabeth.

31:03.080 --> 31:04.680
Really?

31:04.680 --> 31:06.880
I-I think it'd be
more manageable

31:06.880 --> 31:08.480
just thew two of us and Georgie.

31:08.480 --> 31:11.760
I mean just we two women.

31:11.760 --> 31:14.240
And Georgie, if we must.

31:14.240 --> 31:16.360
Y-You're not thinking straight.

31:16.360 --> 31:18.560
One minute you don't want
her interference, and now --

31:18.560 --> 31:23.560
Will you please listen to me
and respect my decision?

31:23.560 --> 31:25.360
You're making a mistake.

31:25.960 --> 31:27.680
Perhaps I am.

31:28.640 --> 31:30.960
But at least it's mine.

31:40.080 --> 31:42.320
[ Birds chirping ]

31:45.440 --> 31:47.520
[ Sighs ]

31:50.840 --> 31:54.640
I could throttle Andrew
with my bare hands.

31:54.640 --> 31:57.760
I had no idea all these years.
None.

31:57.760 --> 32:01.440
It's a secret Olivia
would have taken to her grave.

32:04.560 --> 32:06.400
Except I can't believe

32:06.400 --> 32:08.720
that he tried to use it
to his advantage.

32:09.360 --> 32:12.520
I mean, that really was
Andrew's ratbag period.

32:12.520 --> 32:14.320
I mean, now, of course,
he's a lovely young man.

32:14.320 --> 32:17.160
He's out there
changing the world.

32:17.160 --> 32:20.560
But that's...a little bit
too late for her --

32:20.560 --> 32:22.720
and for all of you.

32:22.720 --> 32:24.680
I feel so ashamed.

32:24.680 --> 32:27.080
Oh, please don't be.

32:27.640 --> 32:30.680
Our family loves you --
and Georgie.

32:30.680 --> 32:33.520
Oh, there's nothing you can say,
really.

32:33.520 --> 32:36.480
I think I'll go and take a bath
before dinner.

32:36.480 --> 32:38.440
-And drown myself.
-[ Laughs ]

32:38.440 --> 32:41.640
[ Chuckles ]
Honestly. Children.

32:41.640 --> 32:43.280
Who'd have them?

32:45.400 --> 32:47.640
[ Clock ticking ]

32:50.240 --> 32:52.880
[ Insects chirping,
dog barking in distance ]

32:58.120 --> 32:59.760
Oh.

33:04.760 --> 33:08.360
A present from Georgie.

33:11.480 --> 33:13.280
He thought it might be
a nice thing

33:13.280 --> 33:15.120
for ladies
to put their earrings in.

33:18.600 --> 33:20.560
Now I might never see him again.

33:20.560 --> 33:21.440
Oh.

33:24.920 --> 33:27.000
It's all too bad.

33:31.040 --> 33:32.520
I...

33:37.080 --> 33:39.680
Some years before I met you...

33:39.680 --> 33:41.600
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

33:43.760 --> 33:45.400
...I had a baby.

33:47.800 --> 33:49.240
And I had to give her up.

33:50.840 --> 33:53.120
I am so sorry.

33:55.200 --> 33:57.920
It's all a bit too close
to the bone.

33:58.600 --> 34:00.280
Of course.

34:01.520 --> 34:03.360
Of course.

34:05.520 --> 34:07.760
[ Music continues ]

34:13.800 --> 34:16.080
[ Birds chirping ]

34:17.960 --> 34:21.199
You need Mrs. Duncan back,
Sister Bligh.

34:21.840 --> 34:24.159
Filing is not my forte.

34:24.159 --> 34:28.960
But this decoration business,
isn't it right up her alley?

34:28.960 --> 34:32.679
I remember when she first
came back to Inverness.

34:32.679 --> 34:35.120
Her outfits, her colors.

34:35.120 --> 34:36.960
People didn't know
what to think.

34:36.960 --> 34:39.960
But I was familiar with the word
"bohemian,"

34:39.960 --> 34:42.360
and I'd say to them,
"Take no notice.

34:42.360 --> 34:44.679
Miss Carolyn is a bohemian.

34:44.679 --> 34:47.600
And my step-daughter, Anna?

34:50.800 --> 34:53.600
I'm not sure
that the wilds of Bohemia

34:53.600 --> 34:56.760
will protect Miss Anna
in quite the same way.

34:57.880 --> 34:59.120
What are people saying?

35:00.880 --> 35:02.360
I don't like to gossip.

35:03.000 --> 35:05.280
But if you did, then...

35:06.640 --> 35:10.760
Who is the father
is of primary interest.

35:13.000 --> 35:15.240
Well, whatever you can do
to put a stop to rumors,

35:15.240 --> 35:16.480
we'd appreciate.

35:18.440 --> 35:20.520
[ Telephone rings ]

35:22.120 --> 35:24.560
Women's clinic.
Sister Bligh speaking.

35:24.560 --> 35:26.600
Yes, she is.
Right here.

35:26.600 --> 35:28.000
I'll tell her.

35:28.000 --> 35:29.320
Emma's waiting to see you.

35:29.320 --> 35:31.640
Oh!

35:31.640 --> 35:35.400
Do you know, she's becoming just
like the daughter I never had.

35:36.360 --> 35:37.960
Does that sound foolish?

35:37.960 --> 35:39.800
No, it doesn't.

35:40.600 --> 35:42.160
Not at all.

35:42.160 --> 35:44.200
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

35:45.720 --> 35:47.640
[ Door opens ]

35:49.720 --> 35:51.720
Oh.

35:51.720 --> 35:54.760
[ Music continues ]

36:01.120 --> 36:03.120
[ Sheep bleating ]

36:03.120 --> 36:05.720
I could go up there
and take a look if you'd like.

36:05.720 --> 36:08.600
-Appreciate it, Roy.
-Excuse me, sir?

36:08.600 --> 36:12.640
Mrs. Collins and Miss Carvolth
to see Mr. Briggs.

36:13.200 --> 36:14.360
You expecting them?

36:15.000 --> 36:16.240
No.

36:17.720 --> 36:19.040
Wish me luck.

36:22.760 --> 36:26.120
It's, um, not always easy
to find it in one's heart

36:26.120 --> 36:29.800
to, you know, mend fences.

36:32.280 --> 36:35.160
And that's all I'll say.

36:43.280 --> 36:44.920
She...

36:45.480 --> 36:49.360
Your mum...
was very proud of you, Em.

36:50.080 --> 36:54.360
The way you study and you got
your head screwed on right.

36:55.840 --> 36:57.920
Y-You should remember that.

36:59.120 --> 37:02.080
If she hadn't met you,
she'd still be alive.

37:02.080 --> 37:04.760
[ Clock ticking ]

37:11.680 --> 37:13.120
That may be true.

37:15.520 --> 37:17.720
She was too old to have a baby.

37:18.840 --> 37:20.880
It wasn't planned.

37:22.680 --> 37:26.400
But...once we got over
the shock...

37:28.120 --> 37:30.040
...she w--
she was over the moon.

37:32.720 --> 37:34.160
But...

37:36.720 --> 37:39.600
You blame me, Emma.

37:39.600 --> 37:41.720
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

37:41.720 --> 37:44.480
If it's gonna make it better,
you do that.

37:44.480 --> 37:47.920
You -- You blame me
for the rest of your days.

37:52.280 --> 37:54.160
Mum would be really cranky
if I did.

37:57.920 --> 38:00.680
We'd know about that, for sure.

38:01.280 --> 38:03.360
Yeah.
She'd give you that look.

38:03.360 --> 38:05.960
Wouldn't have to say much,
but...but you knew.

38:07.360 --> 38:11.120
And then half an hour later,
she'd forget about it.

38:13.520 --> 38:16.960
And she'd get cranky at herself
'cause she...

38:16.960 --> 38:19.120
she'd start being nice again.

38:23.360 --> 38:25.160
Maybe a tree?

38:26.160 --> 38:27.640
With a plaque.

38:29.520 --> 38:32.000
[ Music continues ]

38:32.000 --> 38:34.560
With her name on it?

38:34.560 --> 38:35.840
Yeah.

38:35.840 --> 38:37.600
That's what we'll do.

38:39.720 --> 38:42.800
Well, Mum used to say, you know,

38:42.800 --> 38:47.160
"If rich people do these things,
then why not us?"

38:50.440 --> 38:51.880
Why not?

38:53.920 --> 38:56.160
[ Music continues ]

39:05.800 --> 39:08.120
[ Dog barking in distance ]

39:14.680 --> 39:16.600
In we go to visit the nice lady.

39:16.600 --> 39:17.800
Is she nice?

39:18.880 --> 39:20.280
Shall we?

39:22.400 --> 39:24.080
In we go.

39:27.240 --> 39:29.880
[ Hinges squeak ]

39:36.200 --> 39:38.920
Vroom! Vroom! Vroom!

39:41.320 --> 39:44.040
It was a terrible time
back then.

39:44.040 --> 39:45.920
-I'm sure.
-GEORGIE: Beep! Beep!

39:45.920 --> 39:48.720
We didn't even know
she had a boyfriend.

39:48.720 --> 39:51.520
She always kept herself
to herself.

39:51.520 --> 39:54.040
But you can't give up
your newborn and not regret it.

39:54.960 --> 39:56.520
No.

39:56.520 --> 39:59.240
My late husband and I
offered to raise the child,

39:59.240 --> 40:01.040
but Avril was adamant.

40:01.040 --> 40:04.480
And before we knew,
it was adopted out.

40:06.400 --> 40:09.160
Perhaps that's why she's so keen
to see him now.

40:12.080 --> 40:14.080
This makes me so...

40:14.680 --> 40:17.680
Just...thank you.

40:19.960 --> 40:21.560
Just so happy I...

40:21.560 --> 40:23.840
It was so unexpected.

40:23.840 --> 40:26.680
I never thought
this day would come.

40:26.680 --> 40:29.000
A the telephone call and...

40:31.680 --> 40:33.280
Teddy likes watching you.

40:33.280 --> 40:35.320
Yes, he does.

40:35.320 --> 40:37.400
This is teddy's favorite car.

40:37.400 --> 40:38.760
AVRIL:
Oh, is it, now?

40:38.760 --> 40:40.840
And which one's yours?

40:40.840 --> 40:43.520
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

40:54.000 --> 40:57.280
Spotted Roy a little while ago,
seeing off Emma and Doris.

40:57.280 --> 40:59.560
-Emma kissed him goodbye.
-[ Horse whinnies ]

40:59.560 --> 41:00.960
Very good.

41:00.960 --> 41:03.800
At least things are working out
in that department.

41:03.800 --> 41:05.160
Yes.

41:05.160 --> 41:08.120
I wish my problems
were as easily fixed.

41:08.120 --> 41:11.120
[ Man whistles, dog barking ]

41:11.120 --> 41:13.480
That's exactly what you used to
do when you were a little girl.

41:14.560 --> 41:17.240
Except you had to jump up
on a butter box,

41:17.240 --> 41:19.840
as opposed to on your soapbox.

41:26.240 --> 41:30.160
You never stop worrying about
your children, just so you know.

41:31.080 --> 41:33.400
[ Horse whinnies ]

41:33.960 --> 41:36.720
Father.
Your first parenting tip.

41:38.240 --> 41:40.120
And I have a feeling
not my last.

41:44.600 --> 41:47.600
Henry. Hard man to catch.
You got a sec?

41:47.600 --> 41:49.040
Neil Burton.

41:51.120 --> 41:53.120
A man with so many letters
after his name,

41:53.120 --> 41:55.000
he's falling over them.

42:00.640 --> 42:05.120
He's obviously too bombastic,
not the right fit for here.

42:05.120 --> 42:07.600
You want to call him or will I?

42:07.600 --> 42:09.200
I'll do it if you like.
No skin off my nose.

42:09.200 --> 42:11.040
When did you decide this?

42:11.040 --> 42:13.680
Oh, about two minutes
into the interview.

42:13.680 --> 42:15.760
And I assume you feel
the same way.

42:17.080 --> 42:19.400
Well, he'll just go straight
to the board.

42:19.400 --> 42:21.320
Well, we'll cut him off
at the pass.

42:23.080 --> 42:24.480
You arebacking me on this?

42:24.480 --> 42:26.400
He's one of the top surgeons
in the country.

42:27.360 --> 42:29.960
You arebacking me on this?

42:32.160 --> 42:34.160
The writing's on the wall.

42:35.160 --> 42:36.760
He wants this place.

42:36.760 --> 42:38.120
And he'll get it.

42:42.960 --> 42:44.240
Hang on.

42:47.960 --> 42:50.520
Your writing on the wall
is not the same as mine, is it?

42:52.320 --> 42:54.160
He's promised you something.

42:54.960 --> 42:57.000
And you've been avoiding me.

42:58.000 --> 43:00.040
He's offered you a deal.

43:01.320 --> 43:02.880
Spit it out.

43:05.880 --> 43:09.120
His 2IC in general.

43:10.040 --> 43:12.320
Advise on surgical matters.

43:12.320 --> 43:14.160
In general?

43:17.080 --> 43:21.000
And the piece you're leaving out
is he sees you replacing me.

43:22.240 --> 43:24.720
You've talked about buying up
a GP practice somewhere.

43:24.720 --> 43:26.880
Once, about three years ago.

43:28.000 --> 43:30.920
So how did it go
when Mr. Burton laid this out?

43:30.920 --> 43:33.000
You stood up for me, I suppose.

43:33.000 --> 43:34.720
You told him to get stuffed.

43:34.720 --> 43:36.800
"If Duncan gets turfed,
I'll be out the door with him"?

43:36.800 --> 43:38.200
Along those lines?

43:38.200 --> 43:40.520
I am preparing you
for the inevitable.

43:41.440 --> 43:43.360
If it's not me,
it will be somebody else.

43:46.160 --> 43:49.080
Well, the writing on the wall
spells out "Judas" to me.

43:49.920 --> 43:52.000
Get out of my office, please.

43:52.000 --> 43:54.440
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

44:03.400 --> 44:06.720
The wedding's off, by the way --
in case you haven't been told.

44:06.720 --> 44:08.440
Just get out!

44:16.320 --> 44:18.040
Mr. Fox.

44:18.040 --> 44:20.320
Not now.
Not now.

44:39.040 --> 44:41.640
[ Music continues ]

45:04.640 --> 45:08.000
GEORGIE: Now I'm driving off,
over the mountains.

45:08.680 --> 45:11.160
Over the mountains by myself.

45:13.440 --> 45:16.520
Let's put the Morris car
over here with the other one,

45:16.520 --> 45:17.680
shall we?

45:17.680 --> 45:20.200
It's just called Morris,
not the Morris car.

45:22.240 --> 45:24.680
Could Georgie have
a piece of cake?

45:25.640 --> 45:29.640
Oh. Yes,
if it's not too much trouble.

45:29.640 --> 45:31.080
Excuse me, Mummy.

45:31.080 --> 45:33.960
Would you and Mrs. Goddard
take Georgie to the kitchen?

45:33.960 --> 45:35.440
He'd like a piece of cake.

45:35.440 --> 45:38.200
Oh. Yes.

45:46.200 --> 45:48.040
[ Door closes ]

45:50.320 --> 45:53.320
I don't think I've ever been
this happy.

45:53.320 --> 45:55.280
He's grown into
such a lovely boy.

45:57.280 --> 45:58.760
Yes.

46:00.440 --> 46:02.600
He so looks like his father.

46:03.200 --> 46:05.600
It's uncanny, really.

46:07.000 --> 46:09.360
So looks like his father.

46:09.360 --> 46:11.200
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

46:15.000 --> 46:19.320
Like his father and...mine.

46:21.480 --> 46:23.440
His and mine.

46:23.440 --> 46:26.520
[ Music continues ]

46:26.520 --> 46:29.040
Do you understand?

46:31.320 --> 46:33.160
Oh, my God.

46:34.600 --> 46:37.600
After this, it all stopped,
and then he died.

46:40.800 --> 46:44.160
You love him so much, don't you?
Georgie?

46:45.760 --> 46:47.240
Yes.

46:49.120 --> 46:50.800
Yes.

46:55.880 --> 46:58.120
[ Typewriter clicking ]

47:04.920 --> 47:08.240
Mr. Fox would like to see you,
ma'am, outside.

47:08.920 --> 47:11.160
[ Birds chirping ]

47:15.040 --> 47:16.920
Papa said you had a new car.

47:16.920 --> 47:19.320
Bought it yesterday.
Cheer myself up.

47:19.320 --> 47:21.080
It worked.
[ Chuckles ]

47:21.080 --> 47:23.240
Well, would you like to come in?

47:23.240 --> 47:24.560
I should get going.

47:26.240 --> 47:27.640
Well, good luck
with the surgery.

47:27.640 --> 47:29.040
Thank you.

47:29.040 --> 47:30.160
And then?

47:30.160 --> 47:31.800
Greener pastures and all that.

47:31.800 --> 47:33.760
The next chapter in the novel
that is my life.

47:33.760 --> 47:35.280
It's a page-turner.

47:36.440 --> 47:37.760
Henry, are you okay?

47:37.760 --> 47:41.280
I'm just catching up
to how completely right you are.

47:42.040 --> 47:44.360
What I was thinking,
I-I really don't know.

47:46.560 --> 47:47.800
A bientôt.

47:49.520 --> 47:51.080
Henry.

47:51.080 --> 47:53.520
Just -- Wait. Wait.
Henry.

47:53.520 --> 47:56.200
We're going to be parents.
That's not going to disappear.

47:56.200 --> 47:57.600
No, it is not.

47:57.600 --> 48:00.040
[ Engine starts ]

48:00.040 --> 48:02.040
Promise me you'll stay
with friends.

48:02.040 --> 48:04.680
You've got good pals in Sydney.
They'll want you to.

48:04.680 --> 48:05.880
She'll be apples.

48:07.080 --> 48:09.080
[ Engine revs ]

48:12.080 --> 48:14.920
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

48:43.520 --> 48:45.440
[ Brakes squeak ]

49:01.160 --> 49:03.680
[ Door opens ]

49:08.640 --> 49:10.080
MATT:
Where's Georgie?

49:12.400 --> 49:14.040
You've lost him?

49:15.240 --> 49:17.040
I'm not coming back.

49:17.040 --> 49:18.800
What happened?

49:19.720 --> 49:26.560
Avril Newman gave Georgie away
because she'd been broken --

49:26.560 --> 49:30.760
completely broken --
by a man who had convinced her

49:30.760 --> 49:33.440
that what he was doing to her
was out of love.

49:34.240 --> 49:37.800
Whereas in fact
he was brutalizing her

49:37.800 --> 49:40.840
until she no longer knew
which way was up.

49:41.920 --> 49:44.200
Well, is Georgie still there?

49:44.840 --> 49:46.320
He's at Prudence's.

49:47.880 --> 49:49.200
Goodbye, Matt.

49:49.200 --> 49:51.760
Someone will come
to pick up our things.

49:51.760 --> 49:52.760
No.

49:52.840 --> 49:53.920
No!

49:54.000 --> 49:55.280
No!

49:55.280 --> 49:57.680
I love you.
I love you both.

49:57.680 --> 49:58.800
This isn't what I meant.

49:58.800 --> 50:00.920
We have our whole lives
together.

50:01.880 --> 50:05.120
You love your version of me.

50:05.120 --> 50:07.400
The me who will never disagree
with you,

50:07.400 --> 50:12.280
never challenge you,
a level of perfection

50:12.280 --> 50:15.880
you certainly never demand
of yourself.

50:16.720 --> 50:18.560
[ Door opens ]

50:19.720 --> 50:21.360
Livvy, stop.

50:23.440 --> 50:25.640
Please, Livvy, listen to me.

50:25.640 --> 50:27.080
Just stop.

50:27.920 --> 50:28.760
Olivia!

50:29.640 --> 50:31.040
Just wait!

50:31.800 --> 50:34.560
You'll be sorry!
You'll regret this!

50:36.240 --> 50:40.880
Matthew...
I just wanted to say thank you.

50:40.880 --> 50:44.240
I could never reconcile
the Douglas I knew

50:44.240 --> 50:47.240
with the man who had supposedly
ostracized his son.

50:48.600 --> 50:50.600
Now I see you
for who you really are.

50:53.520 --> 50:55.840
You've given me my Douglas back.

50:58.920 --> 51:01.640
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

51:01.640 --> 51:04.880
[ Grunting ]

51:33.720 --> 51:36.000
[ Music continues ]

51:50.840 --> 51:52.880
[ Birds chirping ]

52:06.880 --> 52:08.520
It's you.

52:11.840 --> 52:15.080
Just the car's been sitting here
for a while and, uh...

52:22.080 --> 52:23.520
Where are you trying to get to?

52:34.440 --> 52:36.240
[ Gasps ]

52:36.240 --> 52:38.240
[ Breathing heavily ]

52:38.240 --> 52:41.280
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

52:41.280 --> 52:43.400
Just tell me
where you want to go.

52:46.920 --> 52:48.160
I d--

52:49.120 --> 52:52.200
I...I don't...know.

52:58.880 --> 53:01.040
I don't know.

53:03.080 --> 53:05.000
[ Music continues ]

